{
  "action_id": "211",
  "action_title": "Reduce tillage",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nFour replicated and controlled studies from North America and Canada and the UK and two literature reviews found that some or all bird groups had higher species richness or diversity on reduced-tillage fields, compared to conventional field in some areas. Two replicated and controlled studies from Canada and the UK and a review found that some measures of diversity were lower, or no different, on reduced-tillage fields, compared to conventional fields.\nFive replicated and controlled studies from the USA and Europe, a small study and two reviews all found that some bird species are found at higher densities on fields with reduced tillage than conventional fields. Five replicated and controlled studies from the USA, Canada and Europe, and a review found that some or all species were found at similar or lower densities on reduced-tillage fields compared to conventional fields, with one finding that preferences decreased over time (possibly due to extreme weather) and another finding that preferences were only found in spring. \nTwo controlled studies (one replicated) and a review found evidence for higher productivity, nesting success or earlier laying on reduced tillage fields, compared to conventional fields. One controlled study found no evidence for greater success or larger chicks on reduced-tillage fields."
}

{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and potential drawbacks of reducing tillage on European farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple European countries, reducing or avoiding inversion tillage has been reported to: increase earthworm biomass and, in some cases, species richness; raise the abundance of some invertebrates; increase numbers of some weeds and/or weed species; and benefit some birds, including higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying and shorter foraging distances, and greater late\u2011winter abundance of skylark, seed\u2011eating songbirds and gamebirds on non\u2011inversion/conservation tillage; a review also reported more invertebrate bird\u2011food resources under no\u2011till (126). Additional reported benefits include reduced soil loss and runoff in several trials that included European sites (with mixed results overall) (906), higher soil organic carbon under no\u2011till or reduced tillage in studies that included Europe\u2014with one randomized, replicated trial in Spain finding the opposite\u2014and maintained or increased soil organic matter, improved soil structure, and, in some studies, higher nutrient retention (906). Reported drawbacks or limitations include cases of negative, no, or inconsistent effects on some invertebrates (including earthworms), weeds, mammals, and some bird species, with one study noting declining bird preferences for conservation\u2011tillage fields over time and mixed long\u2011term effects on earthworms; weed responses also varied by crop type (126, 211). Soil physical responses were mixed: some replicated trials (including in Europe) found higher compaction under reduced tillage, and trials from Europe and India found greater soil cracking reduction, higher infiltration, and higher soil water content with conventional ploughing and sub\u2011soiling than with reduced tillage; no\u2011till increased soil loss where crop cover was absent (906). Yield responses included a randomized, replicated study from Portugal reporting no effect of tillage treatment on yield (906).",
  "action_ids": [
    "126",
    "906",
    "211"
  ]
}

