  "relevant_summary": "Across studies of restoring species-rich grassland, six studies reported positive signs of restoration in under five years, 11 within 10 years, and two taking more than 10 years; differences between restored and existing species-rich grasslands were detected nine or even 60 years after restoration [133]. In grasslands restored from arable/bare soil, butterfly communities became increasingly similar to high\u2011quality grasslands over the first 10 years, species richness was higher on grasslands created <10 years ago than on those >20 years old, and in some cases the number of butterfly species on seeded grassland remained similar each year over a 10\u2011year period; some studies found moth abundance did not increase with time since restoration [3929]. For created/restored prairies, abundance of Fender\u2019s blue eggs was greater 5\u201310 years after restoration than at 1\u20132 years, and similar to remnant prairies [3943]. Following tree and shrub removal on wet meadows, marsh fritillary caterpillar webs increased the next year [3971].",
