{
  "action_id": "24",
  "action_title": "Introduce agri-environment schemes to benefit wild bees",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nFour replicated trials in Europe have shown enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on land managed under various European agri-environment schemes, relative to conventionally-managed fields or field margins. These schemes were the Swiss Ecological Compensation Areas (one replicated trial), the German organic arable farming option (one replicated trial), the Dutch botanical and meadow bird agreements (one replicated trial, very low numbers of bee species) and the Scottish Rural Stewardship Scheme (one replicated trial, also included nest-searching queen bumblebees).\nFour replicated trials in Europe found that the number of bees and/or bee species is not enhanced on land managed under agri-environment schemes, including meadow bird agreements in wet grassland in the Netherlands, measures to protect steppe-living birds and compensation measures around a National Park in Spain, and 6 m wide grass field margin strips in England (one replicated trial for each).\nOn a wider landscape scale, two replicated trials in the UK have found bumblebee populations were not enhanced on farmland managed under agri-environment schemes. One trial compared the reproductive success of colonies of the buff-tailed bumblebee Bombus terrestris, the other compared queen bumblebee numbers in spring in conventionally managed field margins, on farms with and without agri-environment schemes."
}

{
  "query": "What are the overall effects of broad-scale agri-environment schemes on farmland biodiversity in Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across Europe, studies report mixed but often positive effects of agri-environment schemes (AES) on farmland biodiversity: for birds, most studies found increases in population size, density or more favourable trends on AES sites, though some studies found negative or no effects, and outcomes could vary with management tier or placement (Action 700). For plants, several studies found AES maintained or had little/no effect on richness or diversity, some found increases, and some found decreases; Environmentally Sensitive Areas in England helped halt loss of semi-natural grasslands but were less effective at enhancing/restoring biodiversity, and flower abundance increased in some Estonian areas (Action 700). For invertebrates, results were mixed: some studies found maintenance or little/no effect and others found increases; bee responses were local rather than landscape-scale in a UK study (Action 700), with additional bee-focused trials across Europe showing both enhanced diversity/abundance under AES and cases with no enhancement, and two UK landscape-scale trials finding no enhancement of bumblebee populations (Action 24). For mammals, UK evidence showed one positive study and three with mixed effects depending on region or species (Action 700). For bats, UK studies reported no significant differences between AES and conventional farms in most cases, with some instances of lower activity on AES farms (Action 962). For amphibians, European evidence includes creation of breeding habitat or increased frog/toad populations in Denmark and Sweden, and higher amphibian species numbers and abundance in Dutch ditches under AES than in conventional management (Action 818). Baseline comparisons noted that some wildlife numbers were higher before AES implementation in certain studies, while two baseline datasets found no overall differences in birds or soil biota between AES and non-AES areas (Action 700).",
  "action_ids": [
