{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and drawbacks of reducing tillage intensity on European farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies from Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany, Hungary, Ireland, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Slovakia, Switzerland and the UK, reducing tillage compared to conventional management was associated with increased biomass, species richness or abundance of earthworms; greater abundance of some non\u2011earthworm invertebrates; increased numbers of some weeds and/or weed species; higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying dates and shorter foraging distances; and greater abundance of some birds (including Eurasian skylark, seed\u2011eating songbirds and gamebirds) in late winter on non\u2011inversion or conservation tillage fields; a review also reported that tillage had negative effects on invertebrate numbers and that no\u2011till systems had more invertebrate bird food resources (ID: 126). However, other studies found negative, no, or inconsistent effects of reduced tillage on some invertebrates (including earthworms), seed bank richness, numbers of some weed species, mammals, and some bird species; one study found bird preferences for conservation tillage fields decreased over time; and crop type influenced weed numbers under different tillage regimes (ID: 126). For amphibians, there is no evidence assessing effects of reduced tillage (ID: 789), and for reptiles, no studies were found evaluating the effects of managing tillage practices (ID: 3488). Comparing no\u2011tillage with reduced tillage in European contexts (mainly Spain and Italy), soils under no\u2011till sometimes had more organic matter, more nitrogen or phosphorus in some comparisons (and similar in others), similar potassium, mostly similar microbial biomass (with one study showing more under no\u2011till in some cases and less in others), fewer denitrifying bacteria, more mites in one study, larger aggregates in some comparisons (and similar in others), mixed results for water\u2011stability, and greenhouse gas emissions that were sometimes lower or similar under